  version: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 255596ce6b91ac640b392e20dd4f8a9e, type: 2}
  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Futility of All Endeavors'
      title: The Futility of All Endeavors
      number: 1
      content: '  The words of the Preacher, the son of David, king in Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CVanity of vanities,\u201D says the Preacher.\u201CVanity of
        vanities! All [that is done without God\u2019s guidance] is vanity [futile,
        meaningless\u2014a wisp of smoke, a vapor that vanishes, merely chasing the
        wind].\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'What advantage does man have from all his workWhich he does under
        the sun (while earthbound)?  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'One generation goes and another generation comes,But the earth remains
        forever.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Also, the sun rises and the sun sets;And hurries to the place where
        it rises again.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'The wind blows toward the south,Then circles toward the north;The
        wind circles and swirls endlessly,And on its circular course the wind returns.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'All the rivers flow into the sea,Yet the sea is not full.To the place
        where the rivers flow,There they flow again.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'All things are wearisome and all words are frail;Man cannot express
        it.The eye is not satisfied with seeing,Nor is the ear filled with hearing.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'That which has been is that which will be [again],And that which
        has been done is that which will be done again.So there is nothing new under
        the sun.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Is there anything of which it can be said,\u201CSee this, it is new\u201D?It
        has already existed for [the vast] ages [of time recorded or unrecorded]Which
        were before us.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: The Futility of Wisdom'
      title: The Futility of Wisdom
      number: 11
      content: 'There is no remembrance of earlier things,Nor also of the later things
        that are to come;There will be for them no remembranceBy generations who
        will come after them.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'I, the Preacher, have been king over Israel in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And I set my mind to seek and explore by [man\u2019s] wisdom all
        [human activity] that has been done under heaven. It is a miserable business
        and a burdensome task which God has given the sons of men with which to be
        busy and distressed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'I have seen all the works which have been done under the sun, and
        behold, all is vanity, a futile grasping and chasing after the wind. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'What is crooked cannot be straightened and what is defective and
        lacking cannot be counted.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "I spoke with my heart, saying, \u201CBehold, I have acquired great
        [human] wisdom and experience, more than all who were over Jerusalem before
        me; and my mind has observed a wealth of [moral] wisdom and [scientific]
        knowledge.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'And I set my mind to know [practical] wisdom and to discern [the
        character of] madness and folly [in which men seem to find satisfaction];
        I realized that this too is a futile grasping and chasing after the wind. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: For in much [human] wisdom there is much displeasure and exasperation;
        increasing knowledge increases sorrow.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Futility of Pleasure and Possessions'
      title: The Futility of Pleasure and Possessions
      number: 1
      content: "  I said to myself, \u201CCome now, I will test you with pleasure
        and gratification; so enjoy yourself and have a good time.\u201D But behold,
        this too was vanity (futility, meaninglessness). "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "I said of laughter, \u201CIt is madness,\u201D and of pleasure, \u201CWhat
        does it accomplish?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'I explored with my mind how to gratify myself with wine while [at
        the same time] having my mind remain steady and guide me wisely; and how
        to take control of foolishness, until I could see what was good for the sons
        of men to do under heaven all the days of their lives. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'I made great works: I built houses for myself; I planted vineyards
        for myself; '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'I made gardens and orchards for myself and I planted in them all
        kinds of fruit trees; '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'I made pools of water for myself from which to water the forest and
        make the trees bud. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'I bought male and female slaves and had slaves born in my house.
        I also possessed herds and flocks larger than any who preceded me in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Also, I collected for myself silver and gold and the treasure of
        kings and provinces. I provided for myself male singers and female singers,
        and the delights and pleasures of men\u2014many concubines.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'So I became great and excelled more than all who preceded me in Jerusalem.
        My wisdom also remained with me. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Whatever my eyes looked at with desire I did not refuse them. I did
        not withhold from my heart any pleasure, for my heart was pleased because
        of all my labor; and this was my reward for all my labor. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: Wisdom Excels Folly'
      title: Wisdom Excels Folly
      number: 11
      content: 'Then I considered all which my hands had done and labored to do,
        and behold, all was vanity and chasing after the wind and there was no profit
        (nothing of lasting value) under the sun.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'So I turned to consider [secular] wisdom, madness, and folly; for
        what will the man do who succeeds the king? Nothing except what has already
        been done. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Then I saw that [even secular] wisdom [that brings sorrow] is better
        than [the pleasures of] folly and self-indulgence as light excels darkness. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "The wise man\u2019s eyes are in his head, but the fool walks in darkness;
        and yet I know that [in the end] one fate happens to them both. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Then I said to myself, \u201CAs it happens to the fool, so death
        will also happen to me. What use is it then for me to be extremely wise?\u201D
        Then I said in my heart, \u201CThis too is vanity (meaningless).\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'For there is no [more] lasting remembrance of the wise man than of
        the fool, since in the days to come all will be long forgotten. And how does
        the wise man die? Even as the fool! '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: The Futility of Labor'
      title: The Futility of Labor
      number: 17
      content: 'So I hated life, for the work which had been done under the sun caused
        me only great sorrow; because all is futility and chasing after the wind.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'So I hated all the fruit (gain) of my labor for which I had labored
        under the sun, because I must leave it to the man who will succeed me. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'And who knows whether he will be a wise man or a fool? Yet he will
        have control over all the fruit of my labor for which I have labored by acting
        wisely under the sun. This too is vanity (futility, self-conceit). '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'So I turned aside and let my heart despair over all the fruit of
        my labor for which I had labored under the sun. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'For there is a man who has labored with wisdom and knowledge and
        skill, yet gives his legacy to one who has not labored for it. This too is
        vanity and a great evil. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'For what does a man get from all his labor and from the striving
        and sorrow of his heart with which he labors under the sun? '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'For all his days his work is painful and sorrowful; even at night
        his mind does not rest. This too is vanity (worthless).  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'There is nothing better for a man than to eat and drink and assure
        himself that there is good in his labor. Even this, I have seen, is from
        the hand of God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'For who can eat and who can have enjoyment without Him? '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: For to the person who pleases Him God gives wisdom, knowledge, and
        joy; but to the sinner He gives the work of gathering and collecting so that
        he may give to one who pleases God. This too is vanity and chasing after
        the wind.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: A Time for Everything'
      title: A Time for Everything
      number: 1
      content: "  There is a season (a time appointed) for everything and a time
        for every delight and event or purpose under heaven\u2014  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'A time to be born and a time to die;A time to plant and a time to
        uproot what is planted.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'A time to kill and a time to heal;A time to tear down and a time
        to build up.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'A time to weep and a time to laugh;A time to mourn and a time to
        dance.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'A time to throw away stones and a time to gather stones;A time to
        embrace and a time to refrain from embracing.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'A time to search and a time to give up as lost;A time to keep and
        a time to throw away.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'A time to tear apart and a time to sew together;A time to keep silent
        and a time to speak.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'A time to love and a time to hate;A time for war and a time for peace.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'What profit is there for the worker from that in which he labors? '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: God Set Eternity in the Heart of Man'
      title: God Set Eternity in the Heart of Man
      number: 10
      content: 'I have seen the task which God has given to the sons of men with
        which to occupy themselves.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "He has made everything beautiful and appropriate in its time. He
        has also planted eternity [a sense of divine purpose] in the human heart
        [a mysterious longing which nothing under the sun can satisfy, except God]\u2014yet
        man cannot find out (comprehend, grasp) what God has done (His overall plan)
        from the beginning to the end.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'I know that there is nothing better for them than to rejoice and
        to do good as long as they live; '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "and also that every man should eat and drink and see and enjoy the
        good of all his labor\u2014it is the gift of God. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'I know that whatever God does, it endures forever; nothing can be
        added to it nor can anything be taken from it, for God does it so that men
        will fear and worship Him [with awe-filled reverence, knowing that He is
        God]. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'That which is has already been, and that which will be has already
        been, for God seeks what has passed by [so that history repeats itself].  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Moreover, I have seen under the sun that in the place of justice
        there is wickedness, and in the place of righteousness there is wickedness. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "I said to myself, \u201CGod will judge both the righteous and the
        wicked,\u201D for there is a time [appointed] for every matter and for every
        deed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "I said to myself regarding the sons of men, \u201CGod is surely testing
        them in order for them to see that [by themselves, without God] they are
        [only] animals.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'For the [earthly] fate of the sons of men and the fate of animals
        is the same. As one dies, so dies the other; indeed, they all have the same
        breath and there is no preeminence or advantage for man [in and of himself]
        over an animal, for all is vanity. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'All go to the same place. All came from the dust and all return to
        the dust. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Who knows if the spirit of man ascends upward and the spirit of the
        animal descends downward to the earth? '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: So I have seen that there is nothing better than that a man should
        be happy in his own works and activities, for that is his portion (share).
        For who will bring him [back] to see what will happen after he is gone?
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Evils of Oppression'
      title: The Evils of Oppression
      number: 1
      content: '  Then I looked again and considered all the acts of oppression that
        were being practiced under the sun. And behold I saw the tears of the oppressed
        and they had no one to comfort them; and on the side of their oppressors
        was power, but they had no one to comfort them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'So I congratulated and thought more fortunate are those who are already
        dead than the living who are still living. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'But better off than either of them is the one who has not yet been
        born, who has not seen the evil deeds that are done under the sun.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "I have seen that every [effort in] labor and every skill in work
        comes from man\u2019s rivalry with his neighbor. This too is vanity (futility,
        false pride) and chasing after the wind. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'The fool folds his hands [together] and consumes his own flesh [destroying
        himself by idleness and apathy]. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'One hand full of rest and patience is better than two fists full
        of labor and chasing after the wind.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Then I looked again at vanity under the sun [in one of its peculiar
        forms]. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "There was a certain man\u2014without a dependent, having neither
        a child nor a brother, yet there was no end to all his labor. Indeed, his
        eyes were not satisfied with riches and he never asked, \u201CFor whom do
        I labor and deprive myself of pleasure?\u201D This too is vanity (a wisp
        of smoke, self-conceit); yes, it is a painful effort and an unhappy task.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Two are better than one because they have a more satisfying return
        for their labor; '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'for if either of them falls, the one will lift up his companion.
        But woe to him who is alone when he falls and does not have another to lift
        him up. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Again, if two lie down together, then they keep warm; but how can
        one be warm alone?  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'And though one can overpower him who is alone, two can resist him.
        A cord of three strands is not quickly broken.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "A poor yet wise youth is better than an old and foolish king who
        no longer knows how to receive instruction and counsel (friendly reproof,
        warning)\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'for the poor youth has [used his wisdom and] come out of prison to
        become king, even though he was born poor in his kingdom. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "I have seen all the living under the sun join with the second youth
        (the king\u2019s acknowledged successor) who replaces him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: There is no end to all the people; to all who were before them. Yet
        those who come later will not be happy with him. Surely this also is vanity
        (emptiness) and chasing after the wind.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Your Attitude Toward God'
      title: Your Attitude Toward God
      number: 1
      content: '  Guard your steps and focus on what you are doing as you go to the
        house of God and draw near to listen rather than to offer the [careless or
        irreverent] sacrifice of fools; for they are too ignorant to know they are
        doing evil. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Do not be hasty with your mouth [speaking careless words or vows]
        or impulsive in thought to bring up a matter before God. For God is in heaven
        and you are on earth; therefore let your words be few. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'For the dream comes through much effort, and the voice of the fool
        through many words.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'When you make a vow or a pledge to God, do not put off paying it;
        for God takes no pleasure in fools [who thoughtlessly mock Him]. Pay what
        you vow. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'It is better that you should not vow than that you should vow and
        not pay. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Do not allow your speech to cause you to sin, and do not say before
        the messenger (priest) of God that it was a mistake. Why should God be angry
        because of your voice (words) and destroy the work of your hands? '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'For in a multitude of dreams and in a flood of words there is worthlessness.
        Rather [reverently] fear God [and worship Him with awe-filled respect, knowing
        who He is].  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'If you see the oppression of the poor and the denial of justice and
        righteousness in the province, do not be shocked at the sight [of corruption];
        for a higher official watches over another official, and there are higher
        ones over them [looking out for one another]. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: The Folly of Riches'
      title: The Folly of Riches
      number: 9
      content: 'After all, a king who cultivates the field is an advantage to the
        land.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'He who loves money will not be satisfied with money, nor he who loves
        abundance with its gain. This too is vanity (emptiness). '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'When good things increase, those who consume them increase. So what
        advantage is there to their owners except to see them with their eyes? '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The sleep of a working man is sweet, whether he eats little or much;
        but the full stomach (greed) of the rich [who hungers for even more] will
        not let him sleep.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'There is a grievous evil which I have seen under the sun: riches
        being kept and hoarded by their owner to his own misery. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'For when those riches are lost in bad investments and he becomes
        the father of a son, then there is nothing in his hand [for the support of
        the child]. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "As he came naked from his mother\u2019s womb, so he will return as
        he came; and he will take away nothing from all his labor that he can carry
        in his hand. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "This also is a grievous evil\u2014exactly as he was born, so he shall
        die. So what advantage has he who labors for the wind? "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'All of his life he also eats in darkness [cheerlessly, without sweetness
        and light], with great frustration, sickness, and anger.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Behold, here is what I have seen to be good and fitting: to eat and
        drink, and to find enjoyment in all the labor in which he labors under the
        sun during the few days of his life which God gives him\u2014for this is
        his [allotted] reward. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Also, every man to whom God has given riches and possessions, He
        has also given the power and ability to enjoy them and to receive [this as]
        his [allotted] portion and to rejoice in his labor\u2014this is the gift
        of God [to him]. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: For he will not often consider the [troubled] days of his life, because
        God keeps him occupied and focused on the joy of his heart [and the tranquility
        of God indwells him].
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Futility of Life'
      title: The Futility of Life
      number: 1
      content: '  There is an evil which I have seen under the sun, and it weighs
        heavily on men: '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'a man to whom God has given riches and wealth and honor, so that
        he lacks nothing of all that he desires, yet God has not given him the power
        or capacity to enjoy them [all those things which are gifts from God], but
        a stranger [in whom he has no interest succeeds him and] enjoys them. This
        is vanity and it is a [cause of] great distress. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "If a man fathers a hundred children and lives many years, however
        many they may be, but his soul is not satisfied with good things and he is
        not respected and is not given a proper burial [he is not laid to rest in
        the sepulcher of his fathers], then I say, \u201CBetter the miscarriage than
        he, "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'for the miscarriage comes in futility (in vain) and passes into obscurity;
        and its name is covered in obscurity. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'It has not seen the sun nor had any knowledge; yet it has more rest
        and is better off than he. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Even if the other man lives a thousand years twice over and yet has
        seen no good and experienced no enjoyment\u2014do not both go to one place
        [the grave]?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'All the labor of man is for his mouth [for self-preservation and
        enjoyment], and yet the desire [of his soul] is not satisfied. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "For what advantage has the wise man over the fool [for being worldly-wise
        is not the secret to happiness]? What advantage has the poor man who has
        learned how to walk [publicly] among the living [with men\u2019s eyes on
        him; for being poor is not the secret to happiness either]? "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'What the eyes see [enjoying what is available] is better than [craving]
        what the soul desires. This too is futility and chasing after the wind.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Whatever exists has already been named [long ago], and it is known
        what [a frail being] man is; for he cannot dispute with Him who is mightier
        than he. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'For there are many other words that increase futility. What then
        is the advantage for a man? '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: For who [limited by human wisdom] knows what is good for man during
        his lifetime, during the few days of his futile life? He spends them like
        a shadow [staying busy, but achieving nothing of lasting value]. For who
        can tell a man what will happen after him [to his work, his treasure, his
        plans] under the sun [after his life is over]?
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Wisdom and Folly Contrasted'
      title: Wisdom and Folly Contrasted
      number: 1
      content: "  A good name is better than precious perfume,And the day of one\u2019s
        death better than the day of one\u2019s birth.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'It is better to go to the house of mourningThan to go to the house
        of feasting,For that [day of death] is the end of every man,And the living
        will take it to heart and solemnly ponder its meaning.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Sorrow is better than laughter,For when a face is sad (deep in thought)
        the heart may be happy [because it is growing in wisdom].  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The heart of the wise [learns when it] is in the house of mourning,But
        the heart of fools is [senseless] in the house of pleasure.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'It is better to listen to the rebuke of the wise man and pursue wisdomThan
        for one to listen to the song of fools and pursue stupidity.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'For like the crackling of [burning] thorn bushes under a pot,So is
        the laughter of the fool;And this too is vanity (futility).  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'For oppression makes a wise man foolish,And a bribe corrupts the
        [good judgment of the] heart.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'The end of a matter is better than its beginning;Patience of spirit
        is better than haughtiness of spirit (pride).  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Do not be eager in your heart to be angry,For anger dwells in the
        heart of fools.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "Do not say, \u201CWhy were the old days better than these?\u201DFor
        it is not from wisdom that you ask about this.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Wisdom along with an inheritance is goodAnd an [excellent] advantage
        for those who see the sun.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'For wisdom is a protection even as money is a protection,But the
        [excellent] advantage of knowledge is that wisdom shields and preserves the
        lives of its possessors.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Consider the work of God:Who can make straight what He has bent?  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'In the day of prosperity be joyful,But in the day of adversity consider
        thatGod has made the one as well as the other,So that man will not find out
        anything that will be after him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'I have seen everything during my [fleeting] days of futility; there
        is a righteous man who perishes in [spite of] his righteousness, and there
        is a wicked man who lives a long life in [spite of] his wickedness. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Do not be excessively righteous [like those given to self-conceit],
        and do not be overly wise (pretentious)\u2014why should you bring yourself
        to ruin? "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Do not be excessively or willfully wicked and do not be a fool. Why
        should you die before your time? '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'It is good that you take hold of one thing (righteousness) and also
        not let go of the other (wisdom); for the one who fears and worships God
        [with awe-filled reverence] will come forth with both of them.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Wisdom strengthens the wise man more than ten rulers who are in a
        city. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Indeed, there is not a righteous man on earth who always does good
        and who never sins. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'Also, do not take seriously everything that is said, so that you
        will not hear your servant cursing you, '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'for you also know that you too have cursed others many times.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "I have tested all this with wisdom. I said, \u201CI will be wise
        [independently of God],\u201D but true wisdom was far from me. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Whatever has been is far off, deeply remote and exceedingly mysterious.
        Who can discover it [for it is beyond the grasp of man]? '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'I turned around and directed my heart to know, to investigate and
        to seek [skillful and godly] wisdom and the reason for things, and to know
        that wickedness is folly and that foolishness is madness [leading to stupidity
        and recklessness]. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'And I discovered that [of all irrational sins none has been so destructive
        in beguiling one away from God as immoral women for] more bitter than death
        is the woman whose heart is [composed of] snares and nets, and whose hands
        are chains. Whoever pleases God will escape from her, but the sinner will
        be taken captive by her [evil].  '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "\u201CBehold, I have discovered this,\u201D says the Preacher, \u201Cwhile
        adding one thing to another to find an explanation, "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'which I am still seeking but have not found. I have found one man
        among a thousand [who pleases God], but I have not found [such] a woman among
        all these [a thousand in my harem]. '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Behold, I have found only this [as a reason]: God made man upright
        and uncorrupted, but they [both men and women] have sought out many devices
        [for evil].\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Obey Rulers'
      title: Obey Rulers
      number: 1
      content: "  Who is like the wise man?And who knows the interpretation of a
        matter?A man\u2019s wisdom illumines his face,And causes his stern face to
        beam.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'I counsel you to keep the command of the king because of the oath
        before God [by which you swore loyalty to him]. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Do not be in a hurry to get out of his presence. Do not join in a
        malevolent matter, for the king will do whatever he pleases.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "For the word of a king is authoritative and powerful,And who will
        say to him, \u201CWhat are you doing?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Whoever keeps and observes a royal command will experience neither
        trouble nor misery;For a wise heart will know the proper time and [appropriate]
        procedure.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "For there is a proper time and [appropriate] procedure for every
        delight,Though mankind\u2019s misery and trouble lies heavily upon him [who
        rebels against the king].  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'For no one knows what will happen;So who can tell him how and when
        it will happen?  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'There is no man who has power and authority over the wind to restrain
        the wind,Nor does he have authority over the day of death;There is no discharge
        [from service] during time of war,And evil will not rescue those who [actively
        seek to] practice it.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'All this I have seen while applying my mind to every deed that is
        done under the sun. There is a time in which one man has exercised power
        over others to their detriment.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'So then, I have seen the wicked buried, those who used to go in and
        out of the holy place [but did not thereby escape their doom], and they are
        [praised in spite of their evil and] soon forgotten in the city where they
        did such things. This too is futility (vanity, emptiness). '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Because the sentence against an evil act is not executed quickly,
        the hearts of the sons of men are fully set to do evil. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'Though a sinner does evil a hundred times and his life [seemingly]
        is prolonged [in spite of his wickedness], still I know that it will be well
        with those who [reverently] fear God, who fear and worship Him openly [realizing
        His omnipresence and His power]. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'But it will not be well for the evil man, nor will he lengthen his
        days like a shadow, because he does not fear God.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'There is a meaningless and futile thing which is done on the earth:
        that is, there are righteous men whose gain is as though they were evil,
        and evil men whose gain is as though they were righteous. I say that this
        too is futility (meaningless, vain). '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Then I commended pleasure and enjoyment, because a man [without God]
        has no better thing under the sun than to eat and to drink and to be merry,
        for this will stand by him in his toil through the days of his life which
        God has given him under the sun.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "When I applied my mind to know wisdom and to see the activities [of
        mankind] that take place upon the earth\u2014how some men seem to sleep neither
        day nor night\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: and I saw all the work of God, I concluded that man cannot discover
        the work that is done under the sun. Even though man may labor in seeking,
        he will not discover; and [more than that], though a wise man thinks and
        claims he knows, he will not be able to find it out.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Men Are in the Hand of God'
      title: Men Are in the Hand of God
      number: 1
      content: '  For I have taken all this to heart, exploring and examining it
        all, how the righteous (those in right standing with God) and the wise and
        their deeds are in the hands of God. No man knows whether it will be love
        or hatred; anything awaits him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'It is the same for all. There is one fate for the righteous and for
        the wicked; for the good, for the clean and for the unclean; for the man
        who offers sacrifices and for the one who does not sacrifice. As the good
        man is, so is the sinner; as he who swears an oath is, so is he who is afraid
        to swear an oath. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'This evil is in all that is done under the sun, that one fate comes
        to all. Also, the hearts of the sons of men are full of evil, and madness
        is in their hearts while they live, and afterwards they go to the dead. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: '[There is no exemption,] but whoever is joined with all the living,
        has hope; surely a live dog is better than a dead lion. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'For the living know that they will die; but the dead know nothing,
        and they no longer have a reward [here], for the memory of them is forgotten. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Indeed their love, their hatred and their zeal have already perished,
        and they will no longer have a share [in this age] in anything that is done
        under the sun.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Go your way, eat your bread with joy and drink your wine with a cheerful
        heart [if you are righteous, wise, and in the hands of God]; for God has
        already approved and accepted your works. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Let your clothes always be white [with purity], and do not let the
        oil [of gladness] be lacking on your head. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: Whatever Your Hand Finds to Do'
      title: Whatever Your Hand Finds to Do
      number: 9
      content: "Live joyfully with the wife whom you love all the days of your fleeting
        life which He has given you under the sun\u2014all the days of vanity and
        futility. For this is your reward in life and in your work in which you have
        labored under the sun.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Whatever your hand finds to do, do it with all your might; for there
        is no activity or planning or knowledge or wisdom in Sheol (the nether world,
        the place of the dead) where you are going.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'I again saw under the sun that the race is not to the swift and the
        battle is not to the strong, and neither is bread to the wise nor riches
        to those of intelligence and understanding nor favor to men of ability; but
        time and chance overtake them all. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'For man also does not know his time [of death]; like fish caught
        in a treacherous net, and birds caught in the snare, so the sons of men are
        ensnared in an evil time when a dark cloud suddenly falls on them.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'This [illustration of] wisdom I have also seen under the sun, and
        great it was to me: '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'There was a little city with few men in it and a great king came
        against it and besieged it and built great battlements against it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'But there was found in it a poor wise man, and by his wisdom he rescued
        the city. Yet no man [seriously] remembered that poor man. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "But I say that wisdom is better than strength, though the poor man\u2019s
        wisdom is despised and his words are not heeded. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'The words of wise men heard in quietness are better than the shouting
        of one who rules among fools. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: Wisdom is better than weapons of war, but one sinner destroys much
        good.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: A Little Foolishness'
      title: A Little Foolishness
      number: 1
      content: '  Dead flies make the oil of the perfumer give off a foul odor; so
        a little foolishness [in one who is esteemed] outweighs wisdom and honor. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "A wise man\u2019s heart turns him toward the right [which is the
        way of blessing], but a fool\u2019s heart turns him toward the left [which
        is the way of condemnation]. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Even when a fool walks along the road, his [common] sense and good
        judgment fail him and he demonstrates to everyone that he is a fool. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'If the temper of the ruler rises against you, do not leave your post
        [showing resistance], because composure and calmness prevent great offenses.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "There is an evil I have seen under the sun, like an error which proceeds
        from the ruler\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'folly is set in many exalted places and in great dignity while the
        rich sit in humble places. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'I have seen slaves riding on horses and princes walking like slaves
        on the ground.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'He who digs a pit [for others] may fall into it, and a serpent may
        bite him who breaks through a [stone] wall. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'He who quarries stones may be hurt with them, and he who splits logs
        may be endangered by them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'If the axe is dull and he does not sharpen its edge, then he must
        exert more strength; but wisdom [to sharpen the axe] helps him succeed [with
        less effort]. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'If the serpent bites before being charmed, then there is no profit
        for the charmer. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "The words of a wise man\u2019s mouth are gracious and win him favor,
        but the lips of a fool consume him; "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'the beginning of his talking is foolishness and the end of his talk
        is wicked madness. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Yet the fool multiplies words, though no man knows what will happen,
        and who can tell him what will come after he is gone? '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'The labor of a fool so wearies him [because he is ignorant] that
        he does not even know how to go to a city. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Woe to you, O land, when your king is a child and when your [incompetent]
        officials and princes feast in the morning. '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Blessed [prosperous and admired] are you, O land, when your king
        is a man of noble birth, and your princes and officials feast at the proper
        time\u2014for strength and not for drunkenness. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Through laziness the rafters [of state affairs] decay and the roof
        sags, and through idleness [the roof of] the house leaks. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'The officials make a feast for enjoyment [instead of repairing what
        is broken], and serve wine to make life merry, and money is the answer to
        everything. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: Moreover, do not curse the king, even in your bedroom, and in your
        sleeping rooms do not curse the rich, for a bird of the air will carry the
        sound and a winged creature will make the matter known.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Cast Your Bread on the Waters'
      title: Cast Your Bread on the Waters
      number: 1
      content: '  Cast your bread on the surface of the waters, [be diligently active,
        make thoughtful decisions], for you will find it after many days. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Give a portion to seven, or even [divide it] to eight, for you do
        not know what misfortune may occur on the earth. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'If the clouds are full [of rain], they empty themselves on the earth;
        and if a tree falls toward the south or toward the north, in the place where
        the tree falls, there it lies. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'He who watches the wind [waiting for all conditions to be perfect]
        will not sow [seed], and he who looks at the clouds will not reap [a harvest]. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Just as you do not know the way and path of the wind or how the bones
        are formed in the womb of a pregnant woman, even so you do not know the activity
        of God who makes all things.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Sow your seed in the morning and do not be idle with your hands in
        the evening, for you do not know whether morning or evening planting will
        succeed, whether this or that, or whether both alike will be good.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'The light is sweet and pleasant, and it is good for the eyes to see
        the sun. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Yes, if a man should live many years, let him rejoice in them all;
        yet let him remember the days of darkness, for they will be many. All that
        is to come will be futility.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Rejoice, young man, in your childhood, and let your heart be pleasant
        in the days of your young manhood. And walk in the ways of your heart and
        in the desires of your eyes, but know that God will bring you into judgment
        for all these things. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: Therefore, remove sorrow and anger from your heart and put away pain
        from your body, for childhood and the prime of life are fleeting.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Remember God in Your Youth'
      title: Remember God in Your Youth
      number: 1
      content: "  Remember [thoughtfully] also your Creator in the days of your youth
        [for you are not your own, but His], before the evil days come or the years
        draw near when you will say [of physical pleasures], \u201CI have no enjoyment
        and delight in them\u201D; "
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'before the sun and the light, and the moon and the stars are darkened
        [by impaired vision], and the clouds [of depression] return after the rain
        [of tears]; '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'in the day when the keepers of the house (hands, arms) tremble, and
        the strong men (feet, knees) bow themselves, and the grinders (molar teeth)
        cease because they are few, and those (eyes) who look through the windows
        grow dim; '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'when the doors (lips) are shut in the streets and the sound of the
        grinding [of the teeth] is low, and one rises at the sound of a bird and
        the crowing of a rooster, and all the daughters of music (voice, ears) sing
        softly. '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Furthermore, they are afraid of a high place and of dangers on the
        road; the almond tree (hair) blossoms [white], and the grasshopper (a little
        thing) is a burden, and the caperberry (desire, appetite) fails. For man
        goes to his eternal home and the mourners go about the streets and market
        places. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Earnestly remember your Creator before the silver cord [of life]
        is broken, or the golden bowl is crushed, or the pitcher at the fountain
        is shattered and the wheel at the cistern is crushed; '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "then the dust [out of which God made man\u2019s body] will return
        to the earth as it was, and the spirit will return to God who gave it. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: Purpose of the Preacher'
      title: Purpose of the Preacher
      number: 8
      content: "\u201CVanity of vanities,\u201D says the Preacher. \u201CAll [that
        is done without God\u2019s guidance] is vanity (futility).\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Furthermore, because the Preacher was wise, he still taught the people
        knowledge; and he pondered and searched out and arranged many proverbs. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'The Preacher sought to find delightful words, even to write correctly
        words of truth.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'The words of the wise are like [prodding] goads, and these collected
        sayings are [firmly fixed in the mind] like well-driven nails; they are given
        by one Shepherd. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'But beyond this my son, [about going further than the words given
        by one Shepherd], be warned: the writing of many books is endless [so do
        not believe everything you read], and excessive study and devotion to books
        is wearying to the body.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'When all has been heard, the end of the matter is: fear God [worship
        Him with awe-filled reverence, knowing that He is almighty God] and keep
        His commandments, for this applies to every person. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: For God will bring every act to judgment, every hidden and secret
        thing, whether it is good or evil.
      comments: []
